<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-722-669  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 722 669.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Dec 17 1990 v7 n49 p14(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microsoft ups ante in bid to integrate NLI technology. (Microsoftinvests another $1 million in Natural Language Inc.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grygo, Gene.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microsoft Corp. (Investment activities)Natural Language Inc. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    MSFT.andO;Topic:     Natural Language InterfacesInvestmentsProduct DevelopmentSoftware Publishers.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Microsoft ups ante in bid to integrate NLI technologyandM;PC software giant Microsoft of Redmond, Wash., has added $1 million to itsprior investments in Natural Language Inc. (NLI) of Berkeley, Calif.,andO;increasing Microsoft's interest to 10 percent in the six-year-old company.andM;The move will boost Microsoft's efforts to integrate NLI's proprietarynatural language database tool technology with Microsoft's product line.andM;When Microsoft first became interested in NLI, that company's technologyrequired more memory and power than was available on personal computers atthe time, said Nathan Myhrvold, Microsoft's vice president of advancedtechnology and business development.andM;&quot;It's just starting to become relative now,&quot; Myhrvold said.andM;PC hardware has matured to the point where it can accommodate the demands ofNLI software, he said.andM;The NLI technology could possibly be integrated with all of Microsoft's majorproduct lines, especially with a future database product that would provideaccess to a database as well as a file system, according to Myhrvold.andM;&quot;We would like to see a system in the future where you'd have the ability toquery a database and file system seamlessly,&quot; he added.andM;Queries would be phrased in English instead of the SQL used with relationaldatabases.andM;NLI's products give users the opportunity to use English commands whenaccessing the Sybase, Oracle, Ingres, Informix and Rdb relational databases.andO;They run on DEC's RISC/Ultrix platforms, other Unix systems and VAX/VMS, NLIofficials said.andM;The close ties between the two companies were first established in June 1987when Microsoft made its initial investment and signed a product licensingagreement, according to officials at both companies.andM;The officials would not disclose the total amount that Microsoft has investedin NLI.andO;</TEXT></DOC>